# issue #1914 — proof that fuse-overlayfs works in the box-dind environment
#
# Captured 2026-06-14 inside a konard/hive-mind-dind container (the same kind
# that runs the bot in production). Establishes that the PR #1926 fix
# (DIND_STORAGE_DRIVER=fuse-overlayfs) starts a working copy-on-write daemon,
# de-risking the "explicit driver = no fallback" behaviour of box's entrypoint.

## Environment probes
$ ls -la /dev/fuse
crw-rw-rw- 1 root root 10, 229 /dev/fuse                 # present (provided by --privileged)
$ command -v fuse-overlayfs ; fuse-overlayfs --version
/usr/bin/fuse-overlayfs
fusermount3 version: 3.14.0 ; fuse-overlayfs: version 1.13-dev
$ grep overlay /proc/filesystems
nodev   overlay
$ docker info --format '{{.Driver}}'
vfs                                                       # forced by ENV DIND_STORAGE_DRIVER=vfs
$ env | grep DIND_STORAGE_DRIVER
DIND_STORAGE_DRIVER=vfs                                   # <-- baked into the OLD Dockerfile.dind

## Root cause (refined)
# box's dind-entrypoint auto-detects: overlay2 -> fuse-overlayfs -> vfs (with
# graceful fallback). It would have picked a copy-on-write driver here. But the
# Hive Mind Dockerfile.dind baked `ENV DIND_STORAGE_DRIVER="vfs"` (commit
# 44d2c29e, "Default DinD storage driver to vfs"), so box used ONLY vfs and never
# tried a CoW driver. The dockerd log confirms it started directly on vfs:
#   level=info msg="Docker daemon" ... storage-driver=vfs version=29.5.3
# (no overlay2/fuse-overlayfs attempts logged).

## Capability proof: a manual fuse-overlayfs mount (what docker's graphdriver does)
$ mkdir -p /tmp/fot/{lower,upper,work,merged}
$ echo hello-from-lower > /tmp/fot/lower/base.txt
$ fuse-overlayfs -o lowerdir=/tmp/fot/lower,upperdir=/tmp/fot/upper,workdir=/tmp/fot/work /tmp/fot/merged
# exit code: 0
$ cat /tmp/fot/merged/base.txt
hello-from-lower                                          # lower layer visible through the overlay
$ echo new-upper-write > /tmp/fot/merged/added.txt
$ ls /tmp/fot/upper/
added.txt                                                 # copy-on-write: writes land in upperdir
$ grep fot/merged /proc/mounts
fuse-overlayfs /tmp/fot/merged fuse.fuse-overlayfs rw,nosuid,nodev,noatime,user_id=1001,group_id=1001,default_permissions 0 0
$ fusermount3 -u /tmp/fot/merged                          # clean unmount

## Conclusion
# fuse-overlayfs mounts and performs copy-on-write here. Docker's fuse-overlayfs
# storage driver uses exactly this mechanism, so DIND_STORAGE_DRIVER=fuse-overlayfs
# yields a working CoW daemon. Under CoW, registering a 498 MB layer costs
# ~498 MB (not the ~30 GB cumulative copy that vfs makes), so the multi-GB image
# fits and "failed to register layer: no space left on device" no longer occurs.
